üåä Our second session of the Youth Adaptation Lab on October 5th focused on the role and function of municipalities and HOW they operate. We are thankful to have been able to learn from Angela Danyluk of the City of Vancouver, and the group was buzzing with questions and curiosities to explore with the Sea2City team. We ended our session by exploring our personal connections to municipal functions and through a series of reflective questions that prompted sharing experiences and stories together. üåä

üåäThe first Youth Adaptation Lab took place on September 28th! 15 eager and engaged youth with deep connections to False Creek were ready to dive into their learning journey about all things sea level rise and coastal adaptation. The cohort will work together over the next year to develop unique project ideas that advance coastal adaptation planning in the City of Vancouver and celebrate the youth voice in those conversations! We spent our first session getting to know each of the participants and the range of experiences and knowledge that each bring to our space. üåä

Join us as we hear from an incredible panel of organizers featuring Hogan‚Äôs Alley Society, Sliced Mango Collective, Sustainabiliteens, and more! Full speaker list coming soon! üåü

What is in a vote and why does yours matter?

Young people make up the largest voting bloc in the country. This means that the power of young people who are engaged in politics can result in real influence and changes to systems that no longer work. 

Get organized for the federal election in an inclusive dialogue on the issues that affect young people in Canada. Discuss issues that matter such as: climate change, racial equity, mental health support and affordable housing.

Tuesday, September 14th
11:00am PDT | 2:00pm EST | Online on Zoom
RSVP at the link in @SFUdialogue bio!

Half informational and half casual conversation, this event will give you space to think about what you care about this election and answer your burning questions on how, when, and where to vote!

üåä Are you feeling anxious or curious about what happens as the City of Vancouver increasingly feels the impacts of climate change? Do you want to be a part of planning and designing for sea level rise? Are you excited about learning with other youth leaders to take climate action? 

This fall, in partnership with the City of Vancouver‚Äôs Sea2City Design Challenge, CityHive is hosting a year long experiential learning opportunity that places youth at the intersection of learning, relationship building, and planning for sea level rise in False Creek. 

Whether you consider yourself a well-read sustainability keener, a creative, an athlete, an entrepreneur, a beginner to climate action, or anything in between, we‚Äôd love for you to participate! 

The Youth Adaptation Lab is designed for youth ages 18-30 of all backgrounds who share a deep connection to False Creek.

Applications are open until August 31st. Apply NOW at the link in our bio! üåä

üèûÔ∏è How can we make public spaces more equitable and inclusive? How can we use our experience of the pandemic to inform the future of our public spaces? What unique experiences do local youth have to shape our public spaces?

Join us on August 25th as Metro Vancouver youth tackle these questions and more!

This event showcases youth projects looking to improve public spaces in Downtown Vancouver and Surrey. Learn about ‚Äòrecess‚Äô at Granville Square, a new public space typology in Surrey, the small town charm of Cloverdale‚Äôs Hawthorne Square, among other exciting initiatives.

These projects provide us with a glimpse of the possibilities for the future of public spaces across Metro Vancouver - straight from the hearts and minds of the 2021 cohort of City Shapers youth.
